urse of a decade). Even a viral hit tweet doesn&#8217;t raise your follower=
 count <em>that </em>much. And what qualifies as a &#8220;big&#8221; accoun=
t keeps increasing as the platform ages; six or seven years ago, 200k would=
 have been a huge number of followers, but now it&#8217;s only OK, since so=
 many other people have now reached 500k or more. In other words, the more =
years Twitter exists, the more years of each person&#8217;s life would be n=
eeded to build up a large amount of social capital on the platform.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em=
 0;">That means that for most people, becoming a big account is simply out =
of reach; they need something else to keep them coming back to the app. For=
